phrase grounding approaches on the Flickr30K Entities test set. A few existing approaches train on Flickr30K Entities train set and report recall@1 while recent methods use COCO train set and report pointing accuracy. Further, all approaches use diï¬€erent visual features making direct comparison diï¬ƒcult. For a fair comparison to state-of-the-art, we use Faster-RCNN trained on Visual Genome object and attribute annotations used in Align2Ground [11] and report performance for models trained on either datasets on both recall and pointing accuracy metrics.
Using the same training data and visual feature architecture, our model shows a 5.7% absolute gain in pointing accuracy over Align2Ground. Learning using our contrastive formulation is also quite sample eï¬ƒcient as can be seen by only a 2 to 3 points drop in performance when the model is trained on the much smaller Flickr30K Entities train set which has approximately one-third as many image-caption pairs as COCO.
3.3 Beneï¬ts of Language Modeling
Our approach beneï¬ts from language modeling in two ways: (i) using the pretrained language model to extract contextualized word representations, and (ii) using the language model to sample context-preserving negative captions. Tab. 2 evaluates along both of these dimensions.
Gains from pretrained word representations. In Tab. 2, BERT (Random) refers to the BERT architecture initialized with random weights and ï¬netuned on COCO image-caption data along with parameters of the attention mechanism. BERT (Pretrained) refers to the oï¬€-the-shelf pretrained BERT model which is used as a contextualized word feature extractor during contrastive learning without ï¬netuning. We observe a âˆ¼10% absolute gain in both recall@1 and pointing accuracy by using pretrained word representations from BERT.

